{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502616","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502616"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:47:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:47:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1882"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1882","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1882"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.65,0.16,0.02,0.03,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1882"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108919"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1882","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1882"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1882"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91288"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"856"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"163"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1596"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45855"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108919","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108919"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man presents to his local General Practitioner with a three month history of non-specific lower abdominal pain. He migrated from Turkey three years ago. He has no other health issues and the physical examination is unremarkable. A contrast-enhanced CT of his abdomen and pelvis is performed and a representative image is shown. (Image)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Calcified gallbladder","Hydatid cyst","Adrenal adenoma","Choledocholithiasis","Gallstone ileus"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThere are areas of calcification throughout the wall of the gallbladder. This is known as a \u003Cstrong\u003Eporcelain gallbladder\u003C/strong\u003E. This is an incidental finding as it is unlikely to be related to the patient\u0027s lower abdominal pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETraditionally, it was recommended that such patients with a porcelain gallbladder should undergo cholecystectomy because of an increased risk of malignancy. More recent studies suggest the risk has been over-estimated and if the patient has no symptoms attributable to the gallbladder, active intervention is not required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERecent reports in the literature suggest that the small, but increased risk of malignancy, is increased where there is selective mucosal calcification as opposed to complete intramural calcification. The recommendations are that the asymptomatic patient with complete intramucosal calcification should be offered reassurance and surveillance and the asymptomatic patient with selective mucosal calcification should be offered surgery. Obviously such a decision would be influenced by the fitness of the patient and observation alone would be appropriate for the patient with co-morbidities or a limited life expectancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst the patient comes from a region in the world where hydatid disease is endemic, the hydatid cysts are more commonly found in the liver and when calcified, the areas of calcification are in the rim and are contiguous. There is nothing on the CT to suggest gallstones - either in the biliary tree or small intestine. There is no evidence of an adrenal adenoma.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The incidental radiological finding of gallbladder calcification does not need any form of active intervention."],"references":["DesJardins H, Duy L, Schierey C, et al. Porcelain Gallbladder: Is Observation a Safe Option in Selected Populations? J Am Coll Surg 2017.11.026"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91288"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1882"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18389"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18389","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18389"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e70b6b4a-c64e-4cde-a54f-87d3966de026.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e70b6b4a-c64e-4cde-a54f-87d3966de026.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":342,"height":391}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91288","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91288"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-14T21:17:40+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-14T21:17:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1882"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108919"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medic